Certainly! Below is a simple HTML file that allows you to upload an image, which will then be scaled to exactly 140x100 pixels. The code includes embedded CSS and JavaScript to handle the image upload and scaling.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Image Resizer</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            text-align: center;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        #output {
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        img {
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Image Resizer</h1>
    <input type="file" id="imageInput" accept="image/*">
    <div id="output"></div>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('imageInput').addEventListener('change', function(event) {
            const file = event.target.files[0];
            if (file) {
                const reader = new FileReader();
                reader.onload = function(e) {
                    const img = new Image();
                    img.src = e.target.result;
                    img.onload = function() {
                        const canvas = document.createElement('canvas');
                        canvas.width = 140;
                        canvas.height = 100;
                        const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
                        ctx.drawImage(img, 0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
                        const scaledImage = canvas.toDataURL();
                        document.getElementById('output').innerHTML = `<h2>Scaled Image (140x100)</h2><img src="${scaledImage}" alt="Scaled Image">`;
                    };
                };
                reader.readAsDataURL(file);
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use:
1. Copy the above code into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `image_resizer.html`).
3. Open the saved file in a web browser.
4. Use the file input to upload an image, and it will display the scaled image of size 140x100 pixels below the input.

This code uses a `<canvas>` element to resize the image and then displays the scaled image on the page.
